{"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"kind":"symbol","metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"title":"PackedInt64Array","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"PackedInt64Array"}],"externalID":"s:10SwiftGodot16PackedInt64ArrayC","roleHeading":"Class","role":"symbol","symbolKind":"class","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"PackedInt64Array"}]},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"platforms":["macOS"],"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"PackedInt64Array"}],"languages":["swift"]}]},{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","anchor":"overview","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"An array specifically designed to hold 64-bit integer values. Packs data tightly, so it saves memory for large array sizes.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"name":"Note","style":"note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This type stores signed 64-bit integers, which means it can take values in the interval "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"[-2^63, 2^63 - 1]"},{"type":"text","text":", i.e. "},{"code":"[-9223372036854775808, 9223372036854775807]","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". Exceeding those bounds will wrap around. If you only need to pack 32-bit integers tightly, see ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt32Array","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" for a more memory-friendly alternative."}]}],"type":"aside"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Differences between packed arrays, typed arrays, and untyped arrays:"}]},{"text":" Packed arrays are generally faster to iterate on and modify compared to a typed array of the same type (e.g. ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt32Array","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" versus "},{"code":"Arrayinteger","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"). Also, packed arrays consume less memory. As a downside, packed arrays are less flexible as they don’t offer as many convenience methods such as "},{"code":"Array\/map(method:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". Typed arrays are in turn faster to iterate on and modify than untyped arrays.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Packed arrays are always passed by reference. To get a copy of an array that can be modified independently of the original array, use "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/duplicate()","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":". This is ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"not"}]},{"type":"text","text":" the case for built-in properties and methods. The returned packed array of these are a copies, and changing it will "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"not","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" affect the original value. To update a built-in property you need to modify the returned array, and then assign it to the property again."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note"}]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/!=(_:_:)-2p5e4","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/+(_:_:)","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/==(_:_:)"],"generated":true,"title":"Operators","anchor":"Operators"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/init()","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/init(_:)-5hacd","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PackedInt64Array\/init(alreadyOwnedContent:)","doc:\/\/SwiftGod